==English==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|worste}}, {{m|enm|wurste}}, {{m|enm|warste}}, {{m|enm|werste}}, {{m|enm|wirste}}, from {{inh|en|ang|wierrest}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*wirsistaz}}, superlative form of {{m|gem-pro|*ubilaz|t=bad, evil}}. Cognate with {{cog|osx|wirsista}}, {{m|osx|wirrista|t=worst}}, {{cog|goh|wirst}}, {{m|goh|wirsesto}}, {{m|goh|wirsisto|t=worst}}, {{cog|da|værst|t=worst}}, {{cog|sv|värst|t=worst}}, {{cog|is|verstur|t=worst}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/wɜːst/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/wɝst/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-worst.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɜː(r)st}}

===Adjective===
{{head|en|superlative adjective}}

# {{en-superlative of|bad}}
## Most [[inferior]]; doing the least [[good]].
##: {{ux|en|I think putting oil on a burn is the '''worst''' thing you can do.}}
## Most [[unfavorable]].
##: {{ux|en|That's the '''worst''' news I've had all day.}}
## Most [[harmful]] or [[severe]].
##: {{ux|en|The '''worst''' storm we had last winter knocked down our power lines.}}
## {{non-gloss definition|Used with the definite article and an implied noun}}: something that is worst.
##: {{ux|en|None of these photographs of me are good, but this one is definitely the '''worst'''.}}
# {{en-superlative of|ill}}
#: {{ux|en|I'm feeling really ill — the '''worst''' I've felt all week.}}

====Usage notes====
The [[comparative degree|comparative]] {{m|en|badder}} (for worse) and [[superlative degree|superlative]] {{m|en|baddest}} (for worst) derived from the [[positive degree|positive]] {{m|en|bad}} are nonstandard. ''Worst'' may be further inflected to form the two additional superlatives ''[[worstest]]'' (nonstandard) and ''[[worstestest]]'' (informal, humorous). The comparative ''[[worser]]'' is also nonstandard.

